::: {#preparing-the-script .section .level3}
### Preparing the script

First, let's upload the data in R markdown (its interface is not
connected to R console). To open the command console in R markdown, you
have to insert the code
"`{r}”. From that, the gray area surrounding it is for inserting the commands. To shut it, you type “`"
below your commands:

``` r
library(readxl) 

data.set <- read_excel("data.set.xlsx") 
data.atributes <- read_excel("variables atributes.xlsx")
```

We will have to load the necessary packages here as well:

Then we can require all sorts of command outputs we want to show in our
R markdown file.
:::

::: {#organizing-the-dataset .section .level3}
### Organizing the Dataset

Add subsets as new columns to the dataset

``` r
df <- data.set %>% mutate(Lvs1_10_15 = ifelse(Dvs1_10_15 < 0, Dvs1_10_15, 0), 
                                          Gvs1_10_15 = ifelse(Dvs1_10_15 > 0, Dvs1_10_15, 0), 
                                          Lvs2_10_15 = ifelse(Dvs2_10_15 < 0, Dvs2_10_15, 0), 
                                          Gvs2_10_15 = ifelse(Dvs2_10_15 > 0, Dvs2_10_15, 0), 
                                          Lvs1_15_18 = ifelse(Dvs1_15_18 < 0, Dvs1_15_18, 0), 
                                          Gvs1_15_18 = ifelse(Dvs1_15_18 > 0, Dvs1_15_18, 0), 
                                          Lvs2_15_18 = ifelse(Dvs2_15_18 < 0, Dvs2_15_18, 0), 
                                          Gvs2_15_18 = ifelse(Dvs2_15_18 > 0, Dvs2_15_18, 0)) 
```

CLEAN DE NAs

``` r
df.na <- na.omit(df) 
```

CLEAN TEXTUAL/DESCRIPTIVE COLLUMNS

``` r
cs <- df.na[,-c(1:5)] 
```
:::

over time (vs10_1).

``` r
ggplot (reg0, aes(y=vs10_1,x=loge_roads)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth (method="lm") 
```

    ## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

![](data:image/png;base64,){width="672"}

In this one we isolated a single explanatory variable with an
'easy-to-get' causal relationship. We can see a significative influence
of distance to roads to the extent of secondary vegetation from 1 to 5
years old in 2010 (fixed year), with an inverse correlation, meaning the
more proximity to roads the less vegetation we have. This was a simple
one!
:::
